# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: php-manual
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] The function parameters are declared in the function signature.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Information may be passed to functions via the argument list, which is a comma-delimited list of expressions.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] The arguments are evaluated from left to right and the result is assigned to the parameters of the function, before the function is actually called (*eager* evaluation).
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] PHP supports passing arguments by value (the default), passing by reference, and default argument values.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Variable-length argument lists and Named Arguments are also supported.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] As of PHP 8.0.0, the list of function parameters may include a trailing comma, which will be ignored.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] That is particularly useful in cases where the list of parameters is long or contains long variable names, making it convenient to list parameters vertically.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] By default, function arguments are passed by value (so that if the value of the argument within the function is changed, it does not get changed outside of the function).
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] To allow a function to modify its arguments, they must be passed by reference.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] It is an error to pass a constant expression as an argument to a parameter that expects to be passed by reference.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] A function may define default values for parameters using syntax similar to assigning a variable.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] The default is used only when the parameter's argument is not passed.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Note that passing **`null`** does *not* assign the default value.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Default parameter values may be scalar values, arrays, the special type **`null`**, and as of PHP 8.1.0, objects using the new ClassName() syntax.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] The default value must be a constant expression, not (for example) a variable, a class member or a function call.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Note that any optional parameters should be specified after any required parameters, otherwise they cannot be omitted from calls.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] As of PHP 8.0.0, named arguments can be used to skip over multiple optional parameters.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] As of PHP 8.0.0, declaring mandatory parameters after optional parameters is *deprecated*.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] This can generally be resolved by dropping the default value, since it will never be used.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] One exception to this rule are parameters of the form `Type $param = null`, where the **`null`** default makes the type implicitly nullable.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] This usage is deprecated as of PHP 8.4.0, and an explicit nullable type should be used instead.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] PHP has support for variable-length argument lists in user-defined functions by using the `...` token.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Parameter lists may include the `...` token to denote that the function accepts a variable number of arguments.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] You may specify normal positional parameters before the `...` token.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] In this case, only the trailing arguments that don't match a positional argument will be added to the array generated by `...`.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] It is also possible to add a type declaration before the `...` token.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] If this is present, then all arguments captured by `...` must match that parameter type.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Finally, variable arguments can also be passed by reference by prefixing the `...` with an ampersand (`&`).
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] PHP 8.0.0 introduced named arguments as an extension of the existing positional parameters.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Named arguments allow passing arguments to a function based on the parameter name, rather than the parameter position.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] This makes the meaning of the argument self-documenting, makes the arguments order-independent and allows skipping default values arbitrarily.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Named arguments are passed by prefixing the value with the parameter name followed by a colon.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Using reserved keywords as parameter names is allowed.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] The parameter name must be an identifier, specifying dynamically is not allowed.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] The order in which the named arguments are passed does not matter.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Named arguments can be combined with positional arguments.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] In this case, the named arguments must come after the positional arguments.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] It is also possible to specify only some of the optional arguments of a function, regardless of their order.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] Passing an argument to the same named parameter multiple times results in an Error exception.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] As of PHP 8.1.0, it is possible to use named arguments after unpacking the arguments.
[src:php-manual/functions-arguments] A named argument *must not* override an already unpacked argument.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] Any valid PHP code may appear inside the body of a function, even other functions and class definitions.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] Function names follow the same rules as other labels in PHP.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] A valid function name starts with a letter or underscore, followed by any number of letters, numbers, or underscores.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] Functions need not be defined before they are referenced, *except* when a function is conditionally defined as shown in the two examples below.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] When a function is defined in a conditional manner such as the two examples shown.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] Its definition must be processed *prior* to being called.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] All functions and classes in PHP have the global scope - they can be called outside a function even if they were defined inside and vice versa.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] PHP does not support function overloading, nor is it possible to undefine or redefine previously-declared functions.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] Both variable number of arguments and default arguments are supported in functions.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] See also the function references for func_num_args(), func_get_arg(), and func_get_args() for more information.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] It is possible to call recursive functions in PHP.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] **Example #4 Recursive functions** **Note**: Recursive function/method calls with over 100-200 recursion levels can smash the stack and cause a termination of the current script.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] Especially, infinite recursion is considered a programming error.
[src:php-manual/functions-user-defined] There are no user contributed notes for this page.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] PHP has an exception model similar to that of other programming languages.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] An exception can be `throw`n, and caught ("`catch`ed") within PHP.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Code may be surrounded in a `try` block, to facilitate the catching of potential exceptions.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Each `try` must have at least one corresponding `catch` or `finally` block.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If an exception is thrown and its current function scope has no `catch` block, the exception will "bubble up" the call stack to the calling function until it finds a matching `catch` block.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] All `finally` blocks it encounters along the way will be executed.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If the call stack is unwound all the way to the global scope without encountering a matching `catch` block, the program will terminate with a fatal error unless a global exception handler has been set.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] The thrown object must be an `instanceof` Throwable.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Trying to throw an object that is not will result in a PHP Fatal Error.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] As of PHP 8.0.0, the `throw` keyword is an expression and may be used in any expression context.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] In prior versions it was a statement and was required to be on its own line.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] A `catch` block defines how to respond to a thrown exception.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] A `catch` block defines one or more types of exception or error it can handle, and optionally a variable to which to assign the exception.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] (The variable was required prior to PHP 8.0.0.) The first `catch` block a thrown exception or error encounters that matches the type of the thrown object will handle the object.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Multiple `catch` blocks can be used to catch different classes of exceptions.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Normal execution (when no exception is thrown within the `try` block) will continue after that last `catch` block defined in sequence.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Exceptions can be `throw`n (or re-thrown) within a `catch` block.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If not, execution will continue after the `catch` block that was triggered.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] When an exception is thrown, code following the statement will not be executed, and PHP will attempt to find the first matching `catch` block.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If an exception is not caught, a PHP Fatal Error will be issued with an "`Uncaught Exception ...`" message, unless a handler has been defined with set_exception_handler().
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] As of PHP 7.1.0, a `catch` block may specify multiple exceptions using the pipe (`|`) character.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] This is useful for when different exceptions from different class hierarchies are handled the same.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] As of PHP 8.0.0, the variable name for a caught exception is optional.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If not specified, the `catch` block will still execute but will not have access to the thrown object.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] A `finally` block may also be specified after or instead of `catch` blocks.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Code within the `finally` block will always be executed after the `try` and `catch` blocks, regardless of whether an exception has been thrown, and before normal execution resumes.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] One notable interaction is between the `finally` block and a `return` statement.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If a `return` statement is encountered inside either the `try` or the `catch` blocks, the `finally` block will still be executed.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Moreover, the `return` statement is evaluated when encountered, but the result will be returned after the `finally` block is executed.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Additionally, if the `finally` block also contains a `return` statement, the value from the `finally` block is returned.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] Another notable interaction is between an exception thrown from within a `try` block, and an exception thrown from within a `finally` block.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If both blocks throw an exception, then the exception thrown from the `finally` block will be the one that is propagated, and the exception thrown from the `try` block will be used as its previous exception.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] If an exception is allowed to bubble up to the global scope, it may be caught by a global exception handler if set.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] The set_exception_handler() function can set a function that will be called in place of a `catch` block if no other block is invoked.
[src:php-manual/language-exceptions] The effect is essentially the same as if the entire program were wrapped in a `try`-`catch` block with that function as the `catch`.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Basic class definitions begin with the keyword `class`, followed by a class name, followed by a pair of curly braces which enclose the definitions of the properties and methods belonging to the class.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The class name can be any valid label, provided it is not a PHP reserved word.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] As of PHP 8.4.0, using a single underscore `_` as a class name is deprecated.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] A valid class name starts with a letter or underscore, followed by any number of letters, numbers, or underscores.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] A class may contain its own constants, variables (called "properties"), and functions (called "methods").
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The pseudo-variable *$this* is available when a method is called from within an object context.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] *$this* is the value of the calling object.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Calling a non-static method statically throws an Error.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Prior to PHP 8.0.0, this would generate a deprecation notice, and *$this* would be undefined.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] As of PHP 8.2.0, a class can be marked with the readonly modifier.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Marking a class as readonly will add the readonly modifier to every declared property, and prevent the creation of dynamic properties.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Moreover, it is impossible to add support for them by using the AllowDynamicProperties attribute.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Attempting to do so will trigger a compile-time error.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] A readonly class can be extended if, and only if, the child class is also a readonly class.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] To create an instance of a class, the `new` keyword must be used.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] An object will always be created unless the object has a constructor defined that throws an exception on error.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Classes should be defined before instantiation (and in some cases this is a requirement).
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] If a variable containing a string with the name of a class is used with `new`, a new instance of that class will be created.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] If the class is in a namespace, its fully qualified name must be used when doing this.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] As of PHP 8.0.0, using `new` with arbitrary expressions is supported.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] This allows more complex instantiation if the expression produces a string.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The expressions must be wrapped in parentheses.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] In the class context, it is possible to create a new object by `new self` and `new parent`.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] When assigning an already created instance of a class to a new variable, the new variable will access the same instance as the object that was assigned.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] This behaviour is the same when passing instances to a function.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] A copy of an already created object can be made by cloning it.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Class properties and methods live in separate "namespaces", so it is possible to have a property and a method with the same name.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Referring to both a property and a method has the same notation, and whether a property will be accessed or a method will be called, solely depends on the context, i.e. whether the usage is a variable access or a function call.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] That means that calling an anonymous function which has been assigned to a property is not directly possible.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Instead the property has to be assigned to a variable first, for instance.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] It is possible to call such a property directly by enclosing it in parentheses.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] A class can inherit the constants, methods, and properties of another class by using the keyword `extends` in the class declaration.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] It is not possible to extend multiple classes; a class can only inherit from one base class.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The inherited constants, methods, and properties can be overridden by redeclaring them with the same name defined in the parent class.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] However, if the parent class has defined a method or constant as final, they may not be overridden.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] It is possible to access the overridden methods or static properties by referencing them with parent::.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] When overriding a method, its signature must be compatible with the parent method.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Otherwise, a fatal error is emitted, or, prior to PHP 8.0.0, an **`E_WARNING`** level error is generated.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] A signature is compatible if it respects the variance rules, makes a mandatory parameter optional, adds only optional new parameters and doesn't restrict but only relaxes the visibility.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] This is known as the Liskov Substitution Principle, or LSP for short.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The constructor, and `private` methods are exempt from these signature compatibility rules, and thus won't emit a fatal error in case of a signature mismatch.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The following examples demonstrate that a child method which removes a parameter, or makes an optional parameter mandatory, is not compatible with the parent method.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Renaming a method's parameter in a child class is not a signature incompatibility.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] However, this is discouraged as it will result in a runtime Error if named arguments are used.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The `class` keyword is also used for class name resolution.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] To obtain the fully qualified name of a class `ClassName` use `ClassName::class`.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] This is particularly useful with namespaced classes.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] As of PHP 8.0.0, `::class` may also be used on objects.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] This resolution happens at runtime, not compile time.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] Its effect is the same as calling get_class() on the object.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] As of PHP 8.0.0, properties and methods may also be accessed with the "nullsafe" operator instead: `?->`.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The nullsafe operator works the same as property or method access as above, except that if the object being dereferenced is **`null`** then **`null`** will be returned rather than an exception thrown.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] If the dereference is part of a chain, the rest of the chain is skipped.
[src:php-manual/language-oop5-basic] The effect is similar to wrapping each access in an is_null() check first, but more compact.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] PHP is a dynamically typed language, which means that by default there is no need to specify the type of a variable, as this will be determined at runtime.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] However, it is possible to statically type some aspect of the language via the use of type declarations.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] Different types that are supported by PHP's type system can be found at the type system page.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] Types restrict the kind of operations that can be performed on them.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] However, if an expression/variable is used in an operation which its type does not support, PHP will attempt to type juggle the value into a type that supports the operation.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] This process depends on the context in which the value is used.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] For more information, see the section on Type Juggling.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] The type comparison tables may also be useful, as various examples of comparison between values of different types are present.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] To check the value and type of an expression, use the var_dump() function.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] To retrieve the type of an expression, use the get_debug_type() function.
[src:php-manual/language-types-intro] However, to check if an expression is of a certain type use the `is_type` functions instead.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] Variables in PHP are represented by a dollar sign followed by the name of the variable.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] A valid variable name starts with a letter (`A-Z`, `a-z`, or the bytes from 128 through 255) or underscore, followed by any number of letters, numbers, or underscores.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] PHP accepts a sequence of any bytes as a variable name.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] Variable names that do not follow the above-mentioned naming rules can only be accessed dynamically at runtime.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] See variable variables for information on how to access them.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] By default, variables are always assigned by value.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] That is to say, when an expression is assigned to a variable, the entire value of the original expression is copied into the destination variable.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] This means, for instance, that after assigning one variable's value to another, changing one of those variables will have no effect on the other.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] For more information on this kind of assignment, see the chapter on Expressions.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] PHP also offers another way to assign values to variables: assign by reference.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] This means that the new variable simply references (in other words, "becomes an alias for" or "points to") the original variable.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] Changes to the new variable affect the original, and vice versa.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] To assign by reference, simply prepend an ampersand (&) to the beginning of the variable which is being assigned (the source variable).
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] One important thing to note is that only variables may be assigned by reference.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] It is not necessary to declare variables in PHP, however, it is a very good practice.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] Accessing an undefined variable will result in an **`E_WARNING`** (prior to PHP 8.0.0, **`E_NOTICE`**).
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] An undefined variable has a default value of **`null`**.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] The isset() language construct can be used to detect if a variable has already been initialized.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] PHP allows array autovivification (automatic creation of new arrays) from an undefined variable.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] Appending an element to an undefined variable will create a new array and will not generate a warning.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] Relying on the default value of an uninitialized variable is problematic when including one file in another which uses the same variable name.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] A variable can be destroyed by using the unset() language construct.
[src:php-manual/language-variables-basics] For information on variable-related functions, see the Variable Functions Reference.
